If so you shouldn&#39;t be doing string replacements because this could open your app to [sql injection](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SQL_injection) attacks.

Instead you should do something like 

```java
try (Connection con = connectionSource.getConnection()) {
   PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(&quot;select * from foo where formId = ? and rateId = ? and validityDate &lt;= ? and creationDate &gt;= ?&quot;);
   ps.setLong(1, formId);
   ps.setLong(2, rateId);
   ps.setTimestamp(3, eventDate);
   ps.setTimestamp(4, eventDate);
   ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery();
   while (rs.next()) {
      ...
   }
}
```

Please see XKCD&#39;s comic related to SQL injection attacks https://xkcd.com/327/

[![enter image description here][1]][1]

  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/gwYNI.png

Adding another answer for the follow up question

&gt; I have a question tho. lets say I have to run this over a loop and create a long string query, should I still use preparedStatement?

When you have complex where clauses, I tend to do something like

```java
public interface ParameterSetter {
   void apply(PreparedStatement ps, int index) throws SQLException;
}
```

```
public List&lt;Person&gt; findPeopleByFilter(PersonFilter filter) {
   List&lt;String&gt; whereClauses = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
   List&lt;ParameterSetter&gt; paramSetters = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
   if (filter.getAge() != null) {
      whereClauses.add(&quot;age = ?&quot;);
      paramSetters.add((ps, i) -&gt; ps.setInt(i, filter.getAge());
   }
   if (filter.getName() != null) {
      whereClauses.add(&quot;name = ?&quot;);
      paramSetters.add((ps, i) -&gt; ps.setString(i, filter.getName());
   }

   // any number of extra where clauses (and their ParameterSetters) are determined here

   String sql = &quot;SELECT * FROM PERSON&quot;;
   if (!whereClauses.isEmpty()) {
      sql += &quot; WHERE &quot; + whereClauses.stream().collect(Collectors.joining(&quot; AND &quot;));
   }

   try (Connection con = getConnection()) {
      PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(sql);
      int index = 1;
      for (ParameterSetter paramSetter : paramSetters) {
         paramSetter.apply(ps, index++);
      }
      ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery();
      List&lt;Person&gt; people = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
      while (rs.next()) {
         ...
      }
      return people;
   }
}



```

